column2: and what it has cost them.

column1: Women who were never taught how to set healthy boundaries.
Women who never got to see a relationship where a woman is revered and respected.
These women’s lives are much more challenging than they seem.
These women feel like they must learn some new language that no one is intentionally teaching them.
These women feel like there is a blind zone that keeps them from experiencing happiness.
Something inside of these women wants to be figured out
column2: but they often have no idea where to begin.

column1: So around the age of 30-40 years old they find themselves disconnected and life seems to have lost it’s magnificence.

column2: I had to learn many new skills and explore female wisdom that doesn’t exist in most families.

Why do some women have it all

let me show you how to heal from the painful relationship with your mother without the constant and continuous drive for her and validation.

3358042272216366055^Video^"Learning to love myself in spite of all the ways I was taught not to has been the greatest gift of healing my mother wound.
There’s still a little time to join the waitlist for my group healing intensive starting in a few weeks.
RESOLVE is a sacred healing space for women who are prepared and willing to do the deep healing work to heal from the relationship with their mother.
And now I live a life that has more joy than I ever thought was possible AND I’m just getting started!
I used to think it could happen for everyone
column2: but it couldn’t happen for me.

column1: I was on the outside looking in with my nose pressed against the glass.
Then I decided to embrace all the hard dark feelings. I invited them in and made them feel at home.
They told me their stories and I didn’t turn away.
I didn’t turn away from myself.
I took responsibility for my peace and my joy. I realized no one can save me but me.
I am the hero in my own story and I love it!

column2: I was still deeply entrenched in my mother‘s way of parenting. I believed in order for me to be a good daughter. I had to be the kind of mother she was.

column1: But then I started to see how damaging that was to the person I love more than anyone in the world.

column2: I’m far from a parenting expert
column3: but I do know that healing my mother wound has been greatest flex in my parenting.

column1: My son feels and knows that he’s seen
column3: known…and it shows in every aspect of his being. He light is so bright that you can’t mistake it for anything other than love.

column1: Being loved by him and having the opportunity to love him
column2: breaks me down on a regular.

column1: Healing is the ONLY thing that made this possible. This is my legacy.

column2: I’m talking about the biggest mistake I made on my healing journey. I thought I could heal alone and intellectualize my trauma

column1: What I learned was complex trauma
column2: created by the relationship with my mother
column3: had to also be healed through a relational dynamic.

column2: I could not do it in my house by myself. I literally had to engage with people and become a part of a community to test the limiting beliefs of me not being good enough or worthy of love.

column1: I also talk about what healing actually is and what it looks like in our lives
column2: so we can know if we’re really taking the necessary steps to achieve the goal at hand.

column1: It’s an all around five ⭐️ banger this week so tap in wherever you listen to podcasts.
Im also planning a Black Mother Wound Group Healing Intensive for May.
The way y’all have been pouring into me and my DM’s over the last month has left me completely shook.😭

I just pulled a few of the most recent messages to show here because I actually have a very hard time letting people love me and appreciate me. That’s a part of my wound that I am healing. And y’all are the ones who are helping ME heal!🫶🏾🥹
I was the girl who never had many friends and thought I was a burden. I looked at life with my nose pressed up against the glass from the outside.

column2: but I was so lonely and felt so unworthy of being loved.

column1: Healing my mother wound did something I never knew it would do. It gave me a place where I belong.
And I think it’s giving everyone here a place where they feel like they belong. And we always deserved this.
And I don’t want you to ever think it’s too late for you to have it.
We really are all in this together and I just want to thank you for rocking with me and being here and showing up the way you do for me and for you.

This is generational trauma breaking work and you have to be ready to go THERE!

column2: commitment and consistency and I’ll be there as your usher
column3: guide and space holder the entire time. I promise I gotchu. ♥️

column1: I don’t have a quick and easy 30 day healing method for you.
But what I can do is teach you how to let go and grieve the loss of a mother you’ll never have.
And then I can show you how to make peace with that and begin to love on yourself in a way that it will make your life completely unrecognizable.
💖Comment “GUIDE” to get my free mother wound healing guide in your DM‘s right now.
The number one thing I hear when people find this community is I thought I was crazy and I thought I was the only one.
Being gaslit your entire life because it’s impossible to believe that you have a mother that isn’t emotionally connected to you can leave your brain and heart scrambled.
This week’s episode we unpack how that gaslighting makes us abandoned and reject ourselves and what to do about it.
Listen today on your favorite podcast platform.

3088670637422205639^Video^"Some of the most helpful + life-changing strategies I use in my every day life for my ADHD may seem simple to an outside perspective.
To you this might just look like a woman wearing gloves to pack boxes.
It’s a strategy I use regularly so my brain doesn’t get exhausted and shut down from simply needing to touch certain materials.
Wearing these gloves to pack means all that energy I would’ve used to suffer through packing (it would’ve been a lottt) I could put towards packing longer
But strategies like this took me DECADES to figure out.
I moved 37 times before I started wearing gloves to pack😱
Not because I didn’t have gloves. I did!
Not because cardboard didn’t bother me. It really (REALLY) did😩
But because I was so used to EVERYTHING being a monumental battle. I was absolutely EXHAUSTED.
My brain couldn’t even fathom the ways I could adapt things in my life (big yes
column2: but especially small!) to help my brain out.

column1: 🔜 This is why I’m creating an ADHD Strategy Building course for ADHDers like me - like you!
Because I know how life-changing these strategies can be

Wireframe is a two-dimensional skeletal outline of an app or webpage
column2: they show the structure and user flow.

column1: Wireframes are used early in the development process to establish the basic structure of a page before visual design and content are added.
You can draw them by hand (like I did) or created them digitally.

column3: and high-fidelity wireframes. The most significant distinguishing factor between these wireframes is the amount of detail they contain.

3088670637422205639^Video^"Some of the most helpful + life-changing strategies I use in my every day life for my ADHD may seem simple to an outside perspective.
To you this might just look like a woman wearing gloves to pack boxes.
It’s a strategy I use regularly so my brain doesn’t get exhausted and shut down from simply needing to touch certain materials.
Wearing these gloves to pack means all that energy I would’ve used to suffer through packing (it would’ve been a lottt) I could put towards packing longer
But strategies like this took me DECADES to figure out.
I moved 37 times before I started wearing gloves to pack😱
Not because I didn’t have gloves. I did!
Not because cardboard didn’t bother me. It really (REALLY) did😩
But because I was so used to EVERYTHING being a monumental battle. I was absolutely EXHAUSTED.
My brain couldn’t even fathom the ways I could adapt things in my life (big yes
column2: but especially small!) to help my brain out.

column1: 3322836626497328112^Image^"Any other thing that you would wanna do other than these?
1. Quantity matter just as much as quality. And not for the reason you think.
We tend to focus so much on WHAT we are posting and way to little on HOW MUCH we are posting.
Because you need TIME and PRACTICE to figure out what works for you. Your first post will suck
column2: and that’s okay. The more you post the better you will get.

column1: 2. The algortiham is not your enemy. The infamous Instagram algorithm is getting blamed left and right for underperformance
Your audience and what they do when they see your content determines how the algortiham will respond to your content.
3. Consistency doesn’t just mean being consistent in how many times you post a week. It also means being consistent with your messaging and content.
Repurposing and reposting the same content and messages is not only beneficial because it saves time but also because it help you set up your brand.
Nobody remembers what you posted on Instagram 3 months ago I promise. Go repurpose that content.
4. The people that will end up buying from you and sign up to work with you - might not follow you at all.
The biggest surprise I ever got was getting messages and calls from people never ever showed up in my notifications. Not even a like or a follow.
That goes to show - those metrics don’t mean nothing for your business.
5. The only people that never saw success on Instagram are the ones that gave up too soon.
This goes for pretty much everything in life but it’s soo true with Instagram as well.
That doesn’t mean you need to just post what you’ve always posted if it doesn’t work - it means you adapt and adjust until you find your thing.

3341804647076941312^Video^"Anxiety can be a temptation for me. Worry can be a temptation for me. Controlling can be a temptation for me.
I used to worry so much and try to control situations. I didn’t know it was possible to love without fear.
There were times when I felt like it was worth it for me to be worried and miserable because somebody had to worry to keep everybody safe.
A couple years ago I realized that carefree isn’t careless. I realized it was safe not to think so much. I realized that anxious thinking is distorted thinking.
I realized you can never get enough of what you don’t need and controlling a situation isn’t going to give me the true sense of safety that I’m looking for.
I know that I made of wisdom and common sense which will always be available to me at the precise moment I needed and never a moment before.
I often scroll away from videos I know aren’t going to be helpful for me in having a sense of trust

3341091970830613129^Video^"After I had my first panic attack which involved the realization and depersonalization
column2: I ramped up how much I was doing for my mental health. I focused even more on getting enough sleep. I ate even “cleaner“. I meditated more. Twice a day. I journal. I tried all different types of therapy for extended periods of time. I tried to exercise but not too much. In essence I became obsessed with anxiety and my mental health.

column1: I felt like my mental health was so fragile and my life became smaller and smaller and anxiety and panic we’re almost all I thought about.
I was afraid to watch a TV show with my husband at the time because I was afraid of the blue light and that I needed to get at least eight hours or else I could panic.
I would look at other people and be so envious that they seem so normal.
I felt so broken because I was doing everything that was recommended and yet I felt worse and worse.
Everything changed for me when I realized that I wasn’t broken and the only problem was that I was innocently over complicating my well-being.
Everything I was doing wasn’t “working” because it was adding stress and even more thinking

3341046184422561975^Video^"Human beings have the best in built healing system. When you understand anxiety and stop resisting it and stop trying to think your way out of it you’re not in a stress response as much. You’re more in your life than in your head. Because you’re not in a state of fight or flight as much your body actually has time to heal. Your body knows how to heal from all the physical symptoms that you’ve been experiencing. You are designed beautifully and designed to come back into balance.

The reason that I had physical symptoms for so long and had so many was because I didn’t know about this and I kept obsessing and researching and innocently over complicating mental and physical well-being.
Once I came into the three principles understanding
column2: which is what I base my coaching on
column3: my physical symptoms started to fall away. Some sooner than others but within a year every single symptom was gone. Some that I’d experience since childhood and just thought was how I was made. I had headaches since before I could swallow a pill. I had stomach aches since elementary school. I struggled with IBS for decades trying so many illumination diets
column6: seeing specialists. Remember the last time I had a headache or a stomachache. My digestion is perfect. I never even thought that was possible. I just thought maybe some of my other symptoms like I floaters and difficulty breathing would fall away. Oh
column7: I also thought I was someone who would always struggle without insomnia. Not true. For the past five years sleep has come so easily to me!

column1: I’ll stop talking about my symptoms
column2: but what I want you to know is if this is possible for you. There is nothing special about me.

column1: PS the symptom that took the longest to go away was what I’d call my breathing thing. I would hold my breath unintentionally then notice and breathe deeply and then would get stuck in the cycle of very labored breathing and focus on my breathing. It lasted so long because I kept checking on it. I kept using it as a marker to see when I would be fully healed…continued in comments

3340497430377204468^Video^"What if the very fact that we’re feeling anxious shows us that we should take everything we think with a grain of salt because it’s most likely untrue?
What if you could take great care of yourself without feeling anxious?

What if you didn’t have to be on guard? What if you could see that when you were hypervigilant and on guard for any physical symptoms you tended to get confused about whether it’s anxiety or something serious?
What if you could see that it was safe not to think so much and that your wisdom in common sense always had your back?

*please note this is when you’ve been checked by your doctor and when you’re not anxious know your symptoms are because of anxiety. I never want anyone to chalk up your physical sensations to anxiety before talking to a doctor. *
